			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Micropatterns in Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_7">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_7</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The paper introduces and studies “micropatterns” to analyze and comprehend grammar-like language descriptions (parsers, metamodels, data models).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It treats grammars and related schema formalisms as meta-languages whose structure can be characterized and compared.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Identifying recurring structural fragments supports grammar comprehension and can inform maintenance/evolution of grammarware artifacts.
</li></ul></li></ul>
